Udio is free to make similar arrangements with other music labels, the music-industry news publication Billboard reported (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW9Gkf3HkQMqW60Zt821Wg8GKW7HlLKX5FwPpVN5l4bkj3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3pQW99ldPZ4PTTPhW1t7_-p9cJC78W6KDdwz77XkCmW5mVKRV2Gst5mW1LGXFG2Hxf40W4jTC9P8YD39WW5Bbhz91NjkglW3tHmmQ7SbdCHW8MW9lB4yqCLgW21CJWj8cxv8zW74VCTS4wf2qHVHv11V4wQN76W8DLxPG1Spdk_W2HqKK03RRQslW2fpCHg5V2DLtW8qVJFB26NNXPW5vST2y6-XjBhW4KvS1f5jPWxxW4bjklt5pWkZmW6Szw735DXhrCN7rCpfn2Tr2RVmYk6g4sQQSVW6xW4_02Q7g9YW8vgr-N10VjTHW7BvT0-1sNWKFW891ycn7my5ZdW9hG2kp2J6KJPW49GmPR6phW06f7ql22x04 ) .

How it works: The platform will allow paying customers to remix, customize, and combine existing recordings and share them with other subscribers.

- Artists must give permission for their recordings to be available on the platform, and they will control how recordings may be used; for instance, to mimic voices or musical styles, change from one style to another, combine one artist’s characteristics with those of another, and the like.
- Artists will receive payments for making their music available for training Udio models plus further compensation for uses of their recordings to produce generated music.
- The new platform will not allow users to download generated music or distribute it via other streaming services. As part of the agreement, Udio briefly terminated the ability to download generated music from its current service and offered subscribers additional credits to generate music to compensate for taking away this capability. After users complained, Udio temporarily restored (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW9Gkf3HkQMqW60Zt821Wg8GKW7HlLKX5FwPpVN5l4bhx5m_5PW50kH_H6lZ3mSN8jygh53DbPSW8p8dnS1-xPFfW356KCS6ZrpCGW549S_V5Gs2ntW1PqcqW8F7GbwVNQxzy8CB3M4W8pSJZK4GPN-KW4h4qQQ3SksB1V_0m-r5F4JhYN6qCv16DJ-4qW5G1MXY7nQM0jW1Kys508Dc_xTN872YlShVM8QW4W4m6v99qQHHW5JPSrs8LK3xmW28mTnx1-8XLDW1rsbvp2XC2W5W26gbPc8TVM68W4rnBr028YD7nN84rRkWh_qTfW4LmJMs1zM2MyW1K2Vff1sdtftW2lxC8h2h48RCW1K2wHY3LwvBFW3QGP769d3c7nN7lf0TBNvD0dVVrtr52Fh3x0W2h6DCv34Wv5lVcGh3S3shCrpW8s-fCs27bzVGW5F165x6rb_WMW5S1cVB7pMhMtf3tFh_q04 )  downloads of existing generated music. - STIM, a Swedish organization that collects royalties on behalf of composers and recording artists, devised (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW9Gkf3HkQMqW60Zt821Wg8GKW7HlLKX5FwPpVN5l4bj65m_5PW69t95C6lZ3pQW2sL8Cj8G-cKcW6f_bkp7GjrKnW5mWBq-8hJQR2W63nvKl5JJcfbW5wzFft9k42SzW4yzF_X3V_Y89W1lM8xJ1GbDWKW2Z_MFW6c2cXdW6yk7dK86K-6bW1G6mry2j2bpDW4hRxdF2BpLQWVN-6-h5_Q0JHN96N2x9MKnbPN1jXK8nfztHPW12tc__6MLHSwW2dGx4M5J3kLkW78BLxC6nvQS9W95W0V576l2q7W3dLkYB99_zY6W3tbqvK3g8MKCW520tLR1-pctBN7VxMSJTr4XCW5mJyKL4kSQYMW5HhC1h8L9YKBN7LdB08MxSC5W4LvbNs6QSqDcW7fB6yF8mwgjQW8kDy9P1CQk2nVzk-x88Qq3zMW2w-t-h6HhtDMN6krCNg6pFpDW66K3t65zx9TlW5jwTdF1dhsy_W8M7VPw8-28gwW5kpDl25NBWYxN6Ny_8xgvd-Df4ybY_b04 ) a license to compensate musicians for use of their works to train AI models.

- In 2023, UMG pressed Apple Music, Spotify, and YouTube to counter (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW9Gkf3HkQMqW60Zt821Wg8GKW7HlLKX5FwPpVN5l4bkj3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3pxW7qLzGw9b8z5lW9lTngF416gm6T5fR_48fVMxW3Rn_P_2gBzN-W79xB_56lHDVHN71fjbynC8knW2wwPwV1rfcGLW3rZW631sqHqfW4MQv8X6wv2-tW5kjc0R2cFyVTW25rLt01LwpxbW1BdxpZ2bgSgjV5M7cD52rv-QW5ZgZ8j2kc6XWW8rMMJr6m7tDXW7lsPql5qdFcKW2rl7GT7SkzDVW99lpYM2xqT5HW18HvTb2s6PsPW3YCMrk1R3pLQW4c-c-M5sl7hxW4T4Hq45V2VbnN1Hm1sWvhg2tW1ydCbJ6KSN0QW4pLfVs3pGwHYW2PZK8x41Mn2ZF62TzlgxNDyW28CsdZ1N-r2hd9zlk204 )  AI-enabled imitations of its artists by blocking AI developers from downloading their recordings. In June

column1: Masking Private Data in Training Sets
Large language models often memorize details in their training data
column2: including private information that may appear only once
column5: or phone number. Researchers built the first open-weights language model that’s guaranteed not to remember such facts.

column3: and colleagues at Google released VaultGemma (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW9Gkf3HkQMqW60Zt821Wg8GKW7HlLKX5FwPpVN5l4bk03prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3mwN82lcMDCvvctW1NWN9r1nCkZ_W4_T49H5k3Kt3N8Wy81qN1c53W2snmlN5zJVl5W3RqT5N8RPj0YV2Nkmb7vnyzYW4CJzZ84scTLVW5K-W652ckxLzW8LWJ2x5JYbt8W26Zqmh6YCP3pVGs3Pl67fJMSW3qN_rs238RY0VDYH6S2Kk2lQW76MX7P8LMfWHW5GLyXM8cXkG2W5jxF3m3yTScFW6FM6tt72KMqfN5RYMhK4dZDHW5n1B0V41FqF6W8PQbfF7xYRQ4W2WX4V27QJYP1W555rGc1XHjByW90g04m3WLfXSW3pbF6Y60fjNKW2ybSrv7r5M4Ff4NwWYx04 )
column4: a 1 billion-parameter model that’s trained from scratch using the technique known as differential privacy. This method prevented the model from memorizing examples that occurred only once in its training data
column5: with a modest sacrifice in performance. Weights are free to download (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW9Gkf3HkQMqW60Zt821Wg8GKW7HlLKX5FwPpVN5l4bjK3prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3n3W7fVmbf2xDszKW14rgjN6ddXDQW2sWt_-3K4lyzW1Gg6fn1dFmjfW4QZXg15rqKzKW5Qg95G4rdbhsW8K-lL287hLvXW1FfNSH6QrmSxN5jxpMdwxkW6N6nC1h7cq87vW8cz2nZ2rtS3KW7sHsTt9bfWPdW4KyM6-6ngy51W8CvGRk2ChJbrVnBYhC5DDll0W6q3RRn5Q_bXpW3dzp_14CFpdKN8ZkQTY82NKVN36CKFm5Jh-bN3NQyPHytKvdW3pXh-b1wYYBHW6jCkPQ6KRRrJW9hwfY47D2FMWW8lpYdy13gdlKd4Z4j804 ) under a license (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW9Gkf3HkQMqW60Zt821Wg8GKW7HlLKX5FwPpVN5l4bjq3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3lTW3qDWmc6Sbyt9W4txQY7194HxkW5PQtTH78KQ5dW7jPZmL364dz1W8fL_wr7JsDmWW5-8qt27Xcm_ZW3L1SGM8vhHL7W2F5gjg5cxbNdW7Q-rzN3-fjqcN8V0MvvWkXjwW5crN7z7x2rwGW82p52b5SsGCfW48yf0X8SRpy8W4hhpK94w6nhSW6rxnVQ6Q5fDnW1_vz4V6_wR34W4z6rSM5SGTgkW8qZ30p7s0wCkN4hGw-HqH1jFW7KLnB849w67sW4MWW4628cRt-W1X0dXD4cVmtyf8P7N8404 )  that allows noncommercial and commercial uses with some restrictions.

column1: Differential privacy basics: An algorithm (such as training a neural network) is differentially private if it’s impossible to tell the difference between its product (the learned weights) and its product given that same dataset minus any given example. Since the presence or absence of a single example can’t significantly change the product
column2: personal information can’t leak from the product (the model’s weights) or the consequences of the product (the model’s outputs). In training a neural network
column3: it’s possible to limit the impact of one example by limiting how much each example’s gradient can impact a model’s weights
column5: by adding noise to each example’s gradient to make it harder to tell from that of other examples.

column1: Key insight: Most previous work (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW9Gkf3HkQMqW60Zt821Wg8GKW7HlLKX5FwPpVN5l4bjq3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3pqW5Bnx3q7Y3TRLW61k5yW5l0x2XW8twHgj7rPmyBF68crZFDxjxW6Nm_Pq8mYqNPW69KcGD6YPjcwW40QPyN5CkX1wW3dyMR25654C_W34dBt33JgT0jW31GD5N2z2prSW6FLbqR1SfGKJW3d1y6c98CLCMW9fHpt_7jvD18VGfJwM1yMX16W5Tndsl9gQJzkW9cTRCR72kN-SW7LV1Jn7J5dMsW72_hxy4CSGzMW46_4Q77hDMr0W2n-FMs4-P9xcW8nBn-25ffV78W4yCh-21c1W6lf33QQ4404 )  applies differential privacy when fine-tuning a model
column2: but that doesn’t prevent the model from memorizing an example during pretraining. Once private information is encoded in the model’s weights
column3: later fine-tuning can’t remove it reliably. Training with differential privacy from the start ensures that such details don’t become embedded in the model.

column1: How it works: VaultGemma follows the same transformer architecture as the 1 billion-parameter version of Google’s Gemma 2. Moreover
column2: the authors pretrained it from scratch on the same 13-trillion-token dataset as Gemma 2 (web
column4: and scientific text). The authors applied differential privacy as VaultGemma learned to predict the next token in sequences of 1

column2: the authors computed the gradient and clipped it so its contribution to the weight update didn’t exceed a fixed threshold. This ensured that any given example didn’t have a disproportionate impact on the weight updates relative to other examples.

column1: - The authors averaged the clipped gradients across each batch and added Gaussian noise to the average before updating the model’s weights. The noise weakened the influence of unique examples while allowing repeated examples to stand out. As a result
column2: the model’s weights became statistically indistinguishable from those of a model trained without any particular 1

column1: Results: VaultGemma showed no measurable memorization across 1 million sequences sampled at random from the training set
column4: and 3 models of roughly similar sizes did. VaultGemma’s average performance across 7 question-answering benchmarks generally matched that of GPT-2 (1.5 billion parameters) but fell short of Gemma models of roughly similar size.

column1: - The authors measured memorization in the Gemma family by the percentage of examples a model could reproduce when given the first half of the sequence. Gemma 3 (1 billion parameters) reproduced 0.0005 percent of training examples tested
column2: while Gemma 2 (2 billion parameters) reproduced 0.04 percent. Gemma 1 (2 billion) reproduced about 1 percent. VaultGemma reproduced 0 percent.

column1: - VaultGemma achieved 39 percent accuracy on HellaSwag (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW9Gkf3HkQMqW60Zt821Wg8GKW7HlLKX5FwPpVN5l4bjq3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3pzN1__pFhfZrKlW14wbKg8K3pJSVpKS2p3JbDNbW842PXG7C3gHFW53wkjx7lNn3RW1n1rKK25Gsh7W3S8P9R6ZxrcwW9504lM6l0ckGW8hz4Kv7Sdl9lW1JLFDV5nyjRRW2MBv2c64VqNBW6VbxtT1Tq0kcW3kX1Bm5vBsGkW3dXRpK7Sjm87W8TbZP54Sd24kW21bDyX4lj35vW7WtVb65fb9YfVRyNls1KvWQ2W742B717Vxc52W3bL6tV1-QWSxVprsD743zmZlVQn0hG5D3-2Hf75c7nn04 )
column2: a benchmark that’s designed to test common-sense reasoning in everyday situations. GPT-2 achieved 48 percent and Gemma 3 (1 billion parameters) reached 61 percent.

column4: while GPT-2 achieved 6 percent and Gemma 3 (1 billion parameters) achieved 40 percent.

column2: but:  The privacy protection comes with a caveat: It applies only to unique examples such as a private phone number that occurs only once in the dataset. If private information appears repeatedly in the training data
column4: a celebrity's street address that leaked and appeared in several publications
column5: the model can learn it as a general pattern.

column1: Why it matters: Private information can find its way into training datasets
column3: a typical large language model may divulge it without the subject’s consent.  VaultGemma shows that large open-weights models can be provably private. While such privacy still comes with a cost — VaultGemma 1B performs roughly on par with models built about five years ago — the results are promising
column4: and future work may close that gap.

column1: We’re thinking: The smartest model for sensitive data might be the one that remembers only the most common information.

10 years working with 3500+ founders through our accelerators, taught us this: 

At the center of every industry you will find an inner circle of people who are

They are the Key People of Influence. 

You probably already know of these people in your industry:

your niche?

A Designer's Guide to AI Prototyping (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWSjhQ3VmD2LW53BBlj6D-rxxW178YCN5BQQz4N7dHCwd3l5QzW95jsWP6lZ3m3W2QRW_n961KqgW559LS762yCyhW6qJ0QB8xYt5bW6ykLqS85YTGBW2hMGm048dGlyW6z09HR1p5ZFJW3679Xl6y1ZpmW6dpfdl6QJLgjN6twN3Nc3rTWW6w7BDS7phCkXF3v5TwrYGS5W98Dsdf5M_dzDW5b81KX51lSP_W6MmzfB3J8LtxW9hskZV4yGTlZW5C8NzG14tYsCVWqc6J2l9VCYW2K8Fcc3X3Dg2W3YvSDY7Pj8DLW1LD2hp5d2lGgW2RFGCS42sYNrW5lwH-x5HGgymW88-mcD6-L6G6W1pqbpG7kkR3CW6gyQ738k6FTnW7LHKwF9lvN0hW62zBnZ4ggqRJW7MjbCc6LSLgRW52gqhL8-4sNLN4fz7223DN71f6DyFHs04 )

- CJ Gammon, Designer Engineering manager at Adobe, offers practical tips—like starting with clear goals, using specific prompts, and embracing imperfection—to make the most of AI-assisted prototyping workflows.

- Rather than aiming for polished results, designers are encouraged to use AI prototypes for rapid exploration, feedback, and better decision-making throughout the design process.

- “Many designers are now leveraging these tools, which range from developer focused code editors to more design friendly Figma plugins and integrations… It gives designers independence and confidence and allows engineers to focus on more technical tasks.”

How to Stand Out When Anyone Can Build Anything (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWSjhQ3VmD2LW53BBlj6D-rxxW178YCN5BQQz4N7dHCvF3l5QzW7Y8-PT6lZ3nrW3zQlPd2wJJS-W9fGx2V4pqhnFW7h4PNk4gH5dKW3KtB8_45FDQ8W2pN7Pj13fpr7W7mJ9975cTN7CW392XDl3nQ9qSW25hmyn5X82txW7zcHHL804R2TW314gHP95mXQcW8yqzjg7N07bfW1fFXTr22ptstW3S5sKL357Dg1N3Xc5ktyKr9RW7Hf0yD6QdG6RW57NgP84xB7qcW7T1Bj047kzNNW5tpl2J7mD5lfW8gBH313YkHPkV4ZKpC60t_sYW58633n7yFFdlW8kqN4j8JL7g9N8sR6LGvfq-sW5jNr0b3XNt7gW4tk6br4cvbxjW1GwHJw8tWrHmf79RwW404 )

- UX designer Anton Sten argues that with AI and no-code tools making it easy for anyone to build, the real challenge isn’t how to build, but what to build in a way that truly matters and resonates.

- Stanton emphasizes that standing out today takes more than quick or trendy features—it requires deep user research, business savvy, clear communication, and genuine craft that turns simple functionality into meaningful experiences.

- “When anyone can build anything, standing out isn’t about better tools or flashier features. It’s about fundamentally different skills that most people skip entirely.”

Ariya Ghoshal (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWSjhQ3VmD2LW53BBlj6D-rxxW178YCN5BQQz4N7dHCtM3l5QzW69sMD-6lZ3p2W8Zj80y1ZC5Q1W4wRq1C8KlQY4VzHM3M2JLPD1W57sndl2t63B2W1VJqH98_-4b-W85Wsy48V1js3W5_Z4pw44JqLvW3QhCVs6bN_pRW663x6Y4gVp7wN5D-cbd_ydvMVRw5034ngTy4W23QnMc1zYx7MW9h6zgv20km5vW4BzKn54qSVWjW8ycj0D5Q4H6WW67zRlW818843W262Qh-1rL5C2W1rxG_M8hySQyW1PvvGN7sybZXW1VtkJt4_qXv8f4-HXBY04 ) , a UX designer with a background in data and research, creates intuitive, purposeful digital experiences that solve real user challenges. Today, we'll look at another way to use landing pages in your business - as a tool for growing your email list. 

Sometimes you just want a sleek, stand-alone page where visitors can sign up for your newsletter, grab your free lead magnet, or join a campaign. 

You don't want them to get distracted by links in your header, but the page should still look and feel like you. Oh, and it would be great if you didn't have to learn a whole new tool to build it.

The good news is you can set up a beautiful email landing page in Podia right now - and it only takes a few minutes!

Here's what to do: 

* Add a new page to your website

* In the page settings, turn the header off

* Add an email form section 

* Use Podia Email to automatically send a welcome email or series when someone signs up

Dear Prospective Student,

Thank you for beginning your application <https://apply.datascience.berkeley.edu/login> for datascience@berkeley, the No.2-ranked online Master of Information and Data Science (MIDS) program at the UC Berkeley School of Information.[1]

For your application to be considered, you must submit the following:

- Completed online application
- Statement of Purpose and additional admissions statements
- Two professional letters of recommendation
- Official transcripts from all educational institutions attended
- Current resume
- Official Graduate Record Examination (GRE) or Graduate Management Admission Test (GMAT) scores (GRE/GMAT waivers available for qualified applicants)
- TOEFL scores (if applicable)
- Application fee of $120 ($140 for international applicants)

We recommend that you request your letters of recommendation and transcripts as soon as possible.

To learn more about application requirements, visit our Admissions Overview <https://ischoolonline.berkeley.edu/admissions/> page. If you have questions, please contact your Admissions Counselor at admissions@datascience.berkeley.edu or 855-678-MIDS.
 
Have Questions During Your Application Process?
Our admissions team is ready to help. Take advantage of our regularly hosted webinars where you can gain insights on the admissions process, application requirements, or any questions you have about our online program. Hey Candace,

 

I’m looking for a special kind of person to join me on a special mission…

 

To take kindness, wisdom, and coaching to people around the world who desperately need it.

 

And I thought of you.

 

You DON’T need any special qualifications or experience to join - I can help you get that.

 

But you do need to answer these 5 questions honestly:

 

1. Do you have a deep desire to serve others?
 

2. Have you been helping/coaching others in the past (even unofficially)?
 

3. Do you enjoy working with other people?
 

4. Are you passionate about being more authentic?
 

5. Do you love to learn and want a new way to grow?

 

If you answered “yes” to most or all of those questions…

 

Then I’d love to have you as part of my mission - and show you how to coach.

 

I’ve put all the details here:

column7: The biggest benefit of being a ghostwriter
column9:
Ghostwriting is the single, most lucrative way to monetize your
talents as a writer.

However, one of the biggest benefits of being a ghostwriter is
that you also get paid in knowledge and skills.

Because you get to work with people who have deep expertise in a
niche or industry.

People who’ve been honing their craft for years, sometimes
decades.

Or even people you admire and look up to.

Thomas here is a great example:

​

--------------------------
Now, there’s a big caveat:
--------------------------

In order to pull this off, you need to acquire some skills:

* Sales
* Positioning
* Free Consulting
* Packing & Pricing

And the harsh truth is:

You won’t master these skills by just reading Twitter Threads &
watching YouTube videos.

You need to roll up your sleeves, start taking action, and put
the reps in.

The good news?

The sooner you start doing that, the faster you will learn these
skills.

And the faster you learn these skills, the faster you will be
able to start getting paid to work AND learn from people you look
up to.

------------------------------------------------------------
So, will you keep waiting for something to magically happen?
------------------------------------------------------------

Or are you going to take the bull by the horns and start making
things happen?

If it’s the latter, then I’d love to be your mentor inside PGA.

Because this is the type of people we love to work with.

column7: Why Your Data Team Doesn't Have A Seat At The Table
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/why-your-data-team-doesnt-have-a

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here 👋
I recently had some great conversations with some data leaders who all started to discuss having a seat at the table. Some referenced how they watched prior leaders they worked for try to take the seat without earning it and how much of a disaster that was. So, I wanted to write about what I’ve learned and seen as data teams try to gain a strategic foothold inside the business.
Before we dive into the article, I’m also excited to share that I’ll be running the second cohort of the Data Leaders Playbook Accelerator. This six-week program is focused on helping data leaders drive more impact and play a larger strategic role in their company. If you’re interested, you can sign up for the program here. [ https://substack.com/redirect/427765e4-6fa3-4349-b299-e5870317ad0e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
With that out of the way, let’s jump into it!
Intro
A lot of data teams want a seat at the table without doing the work to earn it.
They want to be seen as strategic partners. They want influence. But they don’t always understand what actually drives the business.
If you can’t explain how your company makes money, what levers move the needle, or even give a basic overview of its history and context, why should leadership see you as anything more than a task taking organization?
We’ve spent years talking about how business leaders need to become more data-fluent. But not enough people are saying the quiet part out loud: data professionals need to become business-fluent.
How?
By putting in the effort. That means talking to stakeholders, learning how your industry works, understanding your company’s position in the market, and figuring out how data can push it forward. Someone has to bridge the gap between technical execution and business outcomes, and if you lead a data team [ https://substack.com/redirect/f4d5745d-0c46-472a-9ee7-cf8815ffa26c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], that someone is probably you.
The best data engineers, analysts, and scientists I’ve worked with didn’t wait around for executive approval.
They didn’t need permission to drive impact, they found the problems, solved them, and made sure the right people noticed.
It’s not easy. And it’s especially hard to connect the technical work we do with the business outcomes leadership actually cares about.
Ask Yourself - Could The Business Run Without You?
Here’s an important reality: any business that can afford to hire 3–6 people to run a data team and spend six figures on tooling is already doing well. That budget could easily be redirected to any number of initiatives with a clear ROI.
So why did they invest in you?
Seriously…pause and think about that.
Ideally, it’s because they believe data can help amplify what’s already working. That with the right insights, they can move faster, make smarter decisions, and outperform the competition.
But sometimes, the reason is a lot less flattering.
Sometimes, leadership hired a data team because everyone else was doing it. They read a LinkedIn post about being “data-driven,” and boom…now you’re here. In those cases, they don’t necessarily see you as a strategic partner. They see you as back-office support, like accounting.
Can you change that perception? Yes.
Will it be easy? Definitely not.
You’re working with an executive team whose default mindset is cost control, not finding new ways to loop data into strategy. You’ll need consistent wins. Over and over again. Only then will they start to see your team differently.
Now, let’s assume you do work for a company that wants your data team to succeed. A company that sees the potential.
Why, then, are you still struggling to get a seat at the table?
SeattleDataGuy’s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
1) You Don’t Know How To Get Buy-In
It doesn’t matter what kind of leadership you have, whether they want you to be a strategic partner or they’re just going through the motions, you’re still the one who has to secure buy-in for your team’s work.
But leadership doesn’t greenlight every idea. You have to earn their attention. And that starts with understanding what they actually care about.
You might be obsessed with fixing the dbt [ https://substack.com/redirect/4f4ca513-489a-4eed-aef5-02b153c386de?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] repo, migrating to Iceberg [ https://substack.com/redirect/2526332b-a06b-4ba4-af63-d24a43e84faa?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], or optimizing your ETL [ https://substack.com/redirect/4291da6a-e3e2-46cf-9527-62492f5fb855?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
But your CFO doesn’t care. 
Your COO doesn’t care. 
Your CEO definitely doesn’t care.
They care about:
Hitting revenue targets
Improving margins
Reducing churn
Launching faster
Beating competitors
If your data project doesn’t clearly tie to one of those outcomes, it won’t get the attention, or funding, you’re hoping for.
So how do you get buy-in?
Sell the Outcome, Not the Architecture
If you want buy-in, stop leading with your tech stack.
Instead of pitching like this:
🚫 “We want to rebuild the pipeline using XYZ tech to improve freshness and observability.”
Say this instead:
✅ “Right now, the sales team is flying blind for six hours every day waiting on customer lists that are manually created. Not to mention, last week they told us they lost a deal because of this(tie into real things that happened). We can fix that in two weeks. It’ll make the daily forecasting meeting more accurate and reduce the time spent manually reconciling reports.”
Yes, your data team loves the idea of using the newest tools and building their own orchestration tool [ https://substack.com/redirect/5ae581b8-0e56-402a-a9bc-fb7a86dea379?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. But it’s not what is on the businesses mind. 
Understand the Business - A Level Deeper
I’ve written about this before, but it’s worth repeating:
If you don’t understand the business [ https://substack.com/redirect/4d0ed8e1-9988-4843-90d0-ab4f231fc322?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], you can’t play a strategic role. And if you’re not playing a strategic role, why would you ever get a seat at the table?
At best, you’re a high-level IC. Maybe a people manager. But you’re not shaping direction—you’re reacting to it.
Want to know what “understanding the business” actually looks like?
When I talk to highly skilled data leaders, I’m always impressed by how quickly they can shift from technical details to the full context of their business. I recently spoke with a Data VP at a major telecom company, not only could they speak fluently about data, but they also had deep knowledge of:
The history of telecom, including major turning points and key players
How the underlying tech works, modems, networks, and signal types 
Their competitors and how their product positioning stacks up
That’s what I mean when I say to understand the business. Literally all of it.
Because when there’s a big shift in the market or a new tech on the horizon, they need someone who can interpret what that data means in context and recommend a direction.
If you can’t do that, you’ll always be the person someone else hands tasks to.
Deliver Quick Wins With What You Have
I was recently speaking [ https://substack.com/redirect/e7d26944-480b-4756-a35c-d14c3437a630?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] with Lindsay Murphy [ https://substack.com/redirect/3abf0ed1-e5fc-4df7-ad3c-baea703392ac?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], who shared a story about when she first started leading data teams. She asked for budget approval for Looker [ https://substack.com/redirect/1b5a2f95-3e6e-4b73-b934-b99cd7d8989e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. At the time, contracts started at around $30k.
That’s a rounding error for a large enterprise, but at a startup, which is where Lindsay was working, it was a no.
So she got scrappy. She used a free data visualization tool and focused on delivering value quickly. That decision paid off.
Why? Because eventually, leadership started to love what her team was delivering but hated how they had to do it.
They’d say things like:
“We love the weekly reports, but why can’t we pull in other datasets?”
“Why is it so hard to filter or drill down into this dashboard?”
Now, when you come back and say:
“You know how you’re frustrated with X? If we use tool Y, that problem goes away.”
—you’re not making a cold pitch. You’re offering a fix to a problem they already feel.
But this doesn’t happen overnight. You have to earn that moment by proving value first, using whatever tools you already have.
Once you’ve got buy-in, and you’re starting to collect wins, you can start pushing for bigger projects.
But how?
2) Build Champions, Not Just Stakeholders
A stakeholder is someone you work with. A champion is someone who fights for your work when you're not in the room.
If you want to shift how your team is perceived, you need champions, internal allies who believe in your value and actively advocate for your work.
One framework I heard recently captures this well is the Stakeholder Matrix [ https://substack.com/redirect/4949c8e0-13db-47db-98fb-fe2654fb422b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]:
It helps you map out who your stakeholders are, how much influence they have, and who has the potential to become a champion.
Because here’s the thing: in most organizations, decisions aren’t made because one person says, “Let's do X”, unless that person is the CEO.
So, how do you build champions?
Start by deeply understanding their goals:
What metrics do they care about?
What are they on the hook to deliver this quarter?
What’s broken in their workflow that they’ve just come to accept?
And beyond that, get to know them as people.
What do they care about outside of work? What motivates them? We’re all human, and showing genuine interest builds trust.
Then, help them look good.
Don’t wait for a ticket. Offer a proactive solution. Run a back-of-the-napkin analysis. Send a weekly report that saves them an hour. If your work makes their life easier or helps them hit a goal, they’ll remember it, and they’ll talk about it.
These relationships compound over time. And eventually, you’ll start hearing things like:
“We should loop in the data team, they really helped us last time.”
That’s when you know you’re shifting from a service team to a strategic partner.
3) Build Your Internal Marketing Muscle
Many data professionals struggle with internal marketing. They don’t want to “sell” their work. They hate the idea of self-promotion. And honestly, I get it.
But here’s the problem…
If no one knows what your data team is doing, no one will think it’s strategic.
Too many teams do great work in silence, heads down, shipping dashboards and models, while the rest of the org forgets they exist. Then, they’re surprised when leadership questions their value.
You can’t afford to be invisible.
You have to market your impact internally. And yes, that’s your job.
Here’s how to start:
Create a monthly internal update - Share it via Slack or email. Call it "What Data Delivered" or "Insights That Moved the Needle." Have fun with it and keep it short, clear, and focused on outcomes.
Do quick demos at cross-functional or all-hands meetings - People quickly forget what dashboards [ https://substack.com/redirect/1f88b92e-a6f6-4558-8c79-6eae1d5290db?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] exist and what models were deployed. A 5-minute demo, even of something old, can spark interest and re-engagement.
Highlight team wins and user stories - “The support team used to spend four hours a day pulling reports manually. Now it takes 10 minutes.” These stories stick.
Track and share impact metrics:
Hours saved
Revenue influenced
Costs avoided
Decisions accelerated
Give your team credit, loudly and often - Especially if you’re a team lead, make sure leadership knows where the value is coming from.
Remember: visibility drives perception. Perception drives influence. If you want a seat at the table, people need to see you there.
Final Thoughts
Getting a seat at the table is hard. Keeping it is even harder.
I’ve seen plenty of teams grow fast, only to become the architect of their own collapse. The bigger they got, the harder it became to justify their existence. Value didn’t scale with size, and eventually, leadership pulled back.
So keep asking yourself (and your team):
Are we aligned with top company priorities?
Are we solving today’s problems or just optimizing old ones?
Are we surfacing new insights that actually change how people operate?
And above all, remember: your tools, dashboards, and pipelines are just a means to an end.
The end is business impact.
As always, thanks for reading!
Biggest Productivity Killers for Data Engineers - Battling Context Switching and Distraction
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
Accelerating Large-Scale Test Migration with LLMs
Airbnb recently completed our first large-scale, LLM-driven code migration, updating nearly 3.5K React component test files from Enzyme to use React Testing Library (RTL) instead. We’d originally estimated this would take 1.5 years of engineering time to do by hand, but — using a combination of frontier models and robust automation — we finished the entire migration in just 6 weeks.
In this blog post, we’ll highlight the unique challenges we faced migrating from Enzyme to RTL, how LLMs excel at solving this particular type of challenge, and how we structured our migration tooling to run an LLM-driven migration at scale.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/d2af5e4d-8590-4888-9585-8b38b8ce09f9?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]

Hey Candace,

Do you believe this myth about ghostwriting?

“Only CEOs, VCs, and celebrities need ghostwriters.”

Ghostwriting is often seen as this mysterious writing career that
only high-profile people need.

The truth is, anyone who “knows something” needs a ghostwriter.
---------------------------------------------------------------

All business owners or experts in a field, who have information
that would be useful to other people, need a ghostwriter.

Here are just a few examples of people who need ghostwriters:

* Coaches
* Plumbers
* Musicians
* Nutritionists
* Yoga Instructors
* Green Energy scientists

Even Art Museums and Galleries need ghostwriters:

​
Ghostwriting clients are EVERYWHERE.

But these people don’t have the time to write (or have the time
to learn how to write) but they DO have knowledge they want to
share (and other people need).

On the other hand, the ghostwriter DOES have the time to write
but doesn’t have the specific industry experience. It’s a perfect
pairing.

(And we’ve seen people inside PGA charge, $5k, $8k, even $10k+
for ghostwriting projects).

In other words, there’s TONS of opportunity for ghostwriters out
there right now.
-----------------------------------------------------------------

But this doesn’t mean potential clients are just waiting around
for a ghostwriter to fall into their lap.

No, they’re busy, professional people who need a good reason to
stop, think, and consider hiring you as a ghostwriter.

So you won’t be able to capitalize on this lucrative opportunity
if you don’t know how to:

* Position yourself as a Premium Ghostwriter
* Create an Irresistible Offer potential clients can’t refuse
* Deliver a premium service that will mean you can keep upselling
clients

You could spend years trying to figure this out on your own…

Or you could invest in yourself and get up to speed in a fraction
of the time.

-----------------------------------------------------------------

column7: You're invited: Book Launch & Signing - 'Building AI-Powered Products' is here!
column9:
View this post on the web at https://marily.substack.com/p/youre-invited-book-launch-and-signing

THRILLED to announce that my book [ https://substack.com/redirect/5f18a94c-5398-4c69-824e-3e2f746119b4?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], "Building AI-powered Products: the essential guide to AI & GenAI Product Management", is finally here—published by O’Reilly! A unique guide to PMs of ALL levels, especially execs as there is a deep dive in AI strategy & Leadership, based on my learnings from 12 years at Google and Meta.
For 10+ years, I’ve been advocating for AI Product Management. What once was a niche domain has now become essential: 𝗔𝗹𝗹 𝗣𝗠𝘀 𝘄𝗶𝗹𝗹 𝗯𝗲 𝗔𝗜 𝗣𝗠𝘀 𝗶𝗻 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲. O'Reilly means so much to me as it's their books that got me into tech in the first place.
✨ 𝗠𝘆 𝘃𝗶𝘀𝗶𝗼𝗻
I aim to see this curriculum integrated into universities worldwide and empower teams to launch successful AI products. Help spread the word with your universities—share this post, grab your copy, and advocate for this role.
✨ 𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗶𝘀 𝗶𝘁 𝗮𝗯𝗼𝘂𝘁?
It has case studies from AI/GenAI products you use every day, frameworks, a ton of AI tools you may want to experiment with, discusses building AI agents, AI leadership and AI strategy. I taught this material to 10k professionals over the years and it has all my insights as to how execs can bridge the gap between niche AI/GenAI and user needs. 
✨ 𝗕𝗼𝗼𝗸 𝗹𝗮𝘂𝗻𝗰𝗵 𝗲𝘃𝗲𝗻𝘁
Join me for an in-person book launch event on April 17th in the Bay Area at Intuit HQ! We will give out books [ https://substack.com/redirect/c10689b9-fa6d-4aea-8be9-9e5e8f8a5dc8?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] to everyone and I will sign them.  Hope to see you there!

column7: Finding your place at Penn GSE
column9:
Learn about how Penn GSE supports our community

                                      Penn GSE has long been committed to preparing our students to live, work, and lead in a world marked by sweeping demographic change and interconnectedness. We continually reflect on our policies and practices to ensure that they foster an inclusive community of students, faculty, and staff. But there is always much more work to do. We are building the diverse pipeline of educators, leaders, counselors, researchers, entrepreneurs, innovators, and policymakers our world needs.
                                                                           

                                      At Penn GSE, our programs and coursework are centered around addressing inequity across all areas of education. This framework encourages our students to strive for equity in classrooms, boardrooms, governments, and learning settings where true innovation and real transformation become possible.                                    


Learn More <https://www.gse.upenn.edu/about-penn-gse/diversity-inclusion?utm_campaign=inq_aw_all_2024&utm_content=deib&utm_medium=email&utm_source=drip>



                                      Our Research Centers & Initiatives                                    


                                      Our Committee on Race, Equity, and Inclusion <https://www.gse.upenn.edu/explore-by-topic/race-equity-inclusion?utm_campaign=inq_aw_all_2024&utm_content=deib&utm_medium=email&utm_source=drip>, consisting of faculty, staff, and students, has been instrumental in examining issues of bias and cultural inclusivity through open dialogue and continuous learning. This standing committee is focused on addressing school climate and strengthening policies and procedures around such issues as racial bias, LGBTQ+ inclusivity, sexual harassment, and creating a sense of belonging for international students.
                                                                           

                                      We are also home to research groups and training centers such as The Alliance for Higher Education and Democracy (Penn AHEAD), HEARD: The Hub for Equity, Anti-Oppression, Research, and Development, and the Racial Empowerment Collaborative (REC), to name a few.                                    


Learn More <https://www.gse.upenn.edu/academics/research/heard-hub-equity-anti-oppression?utm_campaign=inq_aw_all_2024&utm_content=deib&utm_medium=email&utm_source=drip>


                                      Resources for Students                                    


                                      Our mission is to foster a welcoming and inclusive environment for all Penn GSE students by offering community, financial, and academic support, enabling students to thrive and excel in their educational journey.                                    




                                      Student Organizations & Affinity Groups                                    



                                      Penn GSE's student organizations <https://www.gse.upenn.edu/student/dei-resources-for-students?utm_campaign=inq_aw_all_2024&utm_content=deib&utm_medium=email&utm_source=drip> are founded and managed by students, representing our vibrant community. Additionally, Penn GSE and the University of Pennsylvania partner with students to establish diversity-focused student organizations that are meaningful, relevant, and supportive.                                    




                                      Scholarship & Assistantships                                    



                                      All students, regardless of citizenship, are automatically considered for Penn GSE merit-based scholarships <https://www.gse.upenn.edu/admissions/financial-aid/penngse-scholarships?utm_campaign=inq_aw_all_2024&utm_content=deib&utm_medium=email&utm_source=drip>. Penn GSE also offers all master's applicants the opportunity to apply for a need-based scholarship by completing a survey in the application for admission.                                    




                                      Academic Support & Disability Services                                    



The Weingarten Learning Resource Center <https://weingartencenter.universitylife.upenn.edu/?utm_campaign=inq_aw_all_2024&utm_content=deib&utm_medium=email&utm_source=drip> is Penn's home for Academic Support & Disability Services. They provide services and programs for students who self-identify with disabilities to ensure equal academic opportunities and participation in University-sponsored programs. Learning consultations, tutoring, and interactive programs support students as they further their academic and professional goals.                                    





UNIVERSITY OF PENNSYLVANIA GRADUATE SCHOOL OF EDUCATION


3700 Walnut Street
                                    Philadelphia, PA 19104

column7: Thank you for your application - Data Scientist
column9:
We are excited to hear from you!  Thank you so much for your interest in Intermedia!  We hope that you’ve had a chance to review our career page and Glassdoor to gain insight on our business and culture.  Intermedia is a place where you can indulge your passion for creating and supporting great cloud technology.  At the heart of Intermedia is the people who work here.  We are committed to an inclusive and respectful culture built on transparency and teamwork.

Our talent team will review your background and see if there is a good fit for what we are looking for.  If not now, we will certainly keep your resume on file for future opportunities.  

Thanks again for taking the time to apply!

Kind regards,

Intermedia Talent Acquisition Team

​

Hey Candace,

I just wanted to say a massive thank you once again for being
part of Productivity Spark 2025 🎉

It was such a joy seeing so many of you show up, get stuck in,
and take steps toward smashing your goals for 2025.

If you feel like leaving a little testimonial/review about the
summit and have a spare couple of minutes then we’d love to hear
from you, by clicking here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/zlup3qeldnbnhk92x8zhphwv95g00s6/kkhmh2ulpd86w5ik/aHR0cHM6Ly90ZXN0aW1vbmlhbC50by9hbGktZXZlbnRzLw==
). If not, no worries, we hope you enjoyed the event anyway ❤️

For now, here’s a quick recap of day two + next steps for making
2025 your most productive year yet:

​

🎉 Day 2 Recap (Sunday, 5th January)

1️⃣ Future Sketch Workshop with Izzy

This session was all about designing your dream life, and Izzy
(@izzysealey on YouTube (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/zlup3qeldnbnhk92x8zhphwv95g00s6/58hvh8umwv5kx0a7/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vaXp6eXNlYWxleQ==
) and Instagram (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/zlup3qeldnbnhk92x8zhphwv95g00s6/25h2h9u2xv7490b8/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaW5zdGFncmFtLmNvbS9penp5c2VhbGV5Lz9obD1lbg==
)) guided us through some incredible exercises to help us clarify
our vision and create actionable steps toward our ideal future.
Here’s what we covered:

* The 10-Year Dream - Write down all the big, exciting dreams
you’d love to achieve in the next decade. They can be as wild and
as ambitious as you’d like.
* 3-Year Sketch - Create a compelling 3-year vision by asking
yourself, where would you like to be by 2028? Izzy had us think
through key areas like health, career, personal development, and
relationships.
* The Wheel of Life - The Wheel of Life exercises was a brilliant
way to evaluate where we currently stand in different ares of our
life (health, relationships, finances, etc.), so we have a way to
properly evaluate where we’re making progress and where we’re
falling short. You can complete your wheel of life and track your
progress weekly using Izzy’s tool (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/zlup3qeldnbnhk92x8zhphwv95g00s6/qvh8h8ur378ow0cg/aHR0cHM6Ly9penp5c2VhbGV5LmNvbS93aGVlbA==
).
* Create a Vision Board - To make your vision tangible, Izzy
showed us how to create a vision board. Using Pinterest for
inspiration and Google Slides for organisation, we gathered
images that represent our goals, categorised them by life areas,
and made them easily visible (as wallpaper or even printed out).

​

2️⃣ Design Your Most Productive Year Ever with Ali

In this session, we created our Quarterly Quests - the 90-day
(ish) goals/projects that we’re committed to achieving. And,
ideally, we should have just ONE main Quest each for work and
life for the quarter.

* Set a Work Quest - In WORK, what’s the single most important
goal or project for you to accomplish in the next 3 months?
Recommended approach:
* Set a Life Quest - In LIFE, what’s the single most important
goal or project for you to accomplish in the next 3 months?
* Here’s a useful framework for defining Quests:* Clear statement
of the quest (”My main Quest is to…”)
* Why it’s the most important thing this quarter (”This is the
single most important thing for me to accomplish this quarter
because…”)
* Objective completion criteria by March 31st (”To complete the
Quest, I commit that by 31st March 2025, I’ll have done A, B, and
C”)
* Why it feels exciting and compelling (”This feels really
exciting and compelling for me because…”)
* Specific actions to ensure completion (”To make sure I complete
the Quest, I’m going to…”)

​

3️⃣ Cal Newport’s Special Guest Workshop

Finally, we were joined by Cal Newport, author of Deep Work (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/zlup3qeldnbnhk92x8zhphwv95g00s6/g3hnhwu32de69zs3/aHR0cHM6Ly9jYWxuZXdwb3J0LmNvbS93cml0aW5nLw==
), So Good They Can’t Ignore You (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/zlup3qeldnbnhk92x8zhphwv95g00s6/g3hnhwu32de69zs3/aHR0cHM6Ly9jYWxuZXdwb3J0LmNvbS93cml0aW5nLw==
), and Slow Productivity (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/zlup3qeldnbnhk92x8zhphwv95g00s6/9qhzhdup8qgzwgiz/aHR0cHM6Ly9jYWxuZXdwb3J0LmNvbS9zbG93Lw==
), who did a Q&A sharing his approach to sustainable success and
intentional productivity. Here are some of the key takeaways:

* Discipline is Built, Not Born - Discipline isn’t something
you’re born with, it’s a skill that can be developed
systematically. Cal suggested starting with small, manageable
challenges that push you just enough to grow. Over time, these
incremental steps build the foundation for a disciplined,
productive life.
* Focus on Less, Do It Better - Cal emphasised the importance of
narrowing your focus. Instead of juggling multiple priorities,
choose one or two goals that truly matter and commit to them
fully. This approach allows you to channel your energy into
creating higher-quality work while avoiding the stress of
overcommitting.
* Time-Blocking with Flexibility - Time-blocking is a powerful
tool for structuring your day and maintaining focus on deep work.
But, Cal highlighted the need for flexibility - balance intense
work periods with intentional recovery times. This cyclical
approach prevents burnout and ensures you can sustain high
performance over the long term.
* Lifestyle-Centric Planning - Rather than chasing external
accolades or credentials, Cal advocated for aligning your career
and goals with the lifestyle you want to create. This means
designing your life in a way that supports your personal values
and long-term happiness, rather than simply meeting societal
expectations.
* Combat Perfectionism with Reality-Based Goals - Perfectionism
often leads to paralysis, but Cal offered a way out: focus on
reality-based goals that are both inspiring and achievable. By
exposing yourself to excellence in your field, you can find
motivation and benchmarks for improvement without succumbing to
unrealistic comparisons.

​

🚀 Next Steps - How to Make 2025 Your Most Productive Year Yet

You’ve taken the first step by joining Productivity Spark 2025,
and now it’s time to turn all the incredible insights and
strategies into a real, actionable system that works for you.

That’s exactly what LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/zlup3qeldnbnhk92x8zhphwv95g00s6/3ohphdu78oq4m7up/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcw==
) is designed to do.

This January, I’m running a 3-week LIVE cohort course to help you
build your own Personal Productivity System - a framework to
organise your life, beat procrastination, and take consistent
action toward your biggest goals in 2025.

✅ 3 Weeks of Live Sessions with Me (Ali Abdaal)

We’ll meet every Saturday starting Saturday 18 January 2025, and
I’ll guide you step by step through building your system.

✅ Lowest Price Productivity Cohort Ever

This is the lowest priced productivity cohort I’ve ever run (and
likely ever will).

✅ Lifetime Access to Tools and Templates

You’ll get all the resources you need to build and refine your
productivity system, anytime.

✅ A Proven System for Success

We’ve helped a tonne of students use this system to achieve their

⏳ Don’t Miss Your Chance

Here’s the thing: most people start the year full of excitement

Together, we’ll create a personalised system that keeps you

Hi Candace,

Thank you for expressing interest in attending our Data for Breakfast Training Workshop in New York. Your enrollment into the course has been confirmed.
 

The workshop is taught by Snowflake’s Education team and comprises a four hour step-by-step training on the Snowflake AI Data Cloud. Please bring your own laptop to participate in the workshop.

Course Name: Snowflake Platform Training 
Participant: Candace Grant aicoaching2025@gmail.com
Date: March 11
Time: 11:45 AM - 4:00 PM
Location: NY Marriott Marquis, 1535 Broadway, New York, NY 10036


Add the event to your calendar.
Google Calendar™ <[[https://addcal.co/e/026gxg54bncc/google]]>   |   iCal® <[[https://addcal.co/e/026gxg54bncc/outlook]]>

	- training.snowflake.com/user <http://training.snowflake.com/user>
	- https://docs.snowflake.com/ <https://go.snowflake.net/MjUyLVJGTy0yMjcAAAGZHx1or3KxPKm_4nQNxM12byO8RCJgk51hgeLwqAMJbLD3x9Ur3gyduIc1lfBJ9ImW6oSv2fY=>


	- Student Snowflake lab account access requires ability to access/authenticate via traffic on the ports listed below. Confirm with your IT/Network Admin.

Please note: Recording of any kind during a Snowflake Instructor-led training session is strictly prohibited

Course Material Access:
When class begins, log in to your Training 
Account <https://go.snowflake.net/MjUyLVJGTy0yMjcAAAGZHx1or9XcprUB-bVaufDYOap89s8fOorJwC_KriOJCUfH1-QwPuL294A25c0727C2ddnfO1U=> and click on the course to access your course materials. The content contained during the Snowflake Trainings and in the materials provided for training, including but not limited to the labs, scripts and demos (collectively, the “Training Examples”), are intended to be used as examples only for training purposes and are not intended to be used in a Snowflake 
production environment. To the extent you or your company choose to use such Training Examples it is at your own discretion and risk.

All lab participants who complete their lab will receive a free SnowPro® Associate: Platform

We look forward to having you join us at Data for Breakfast in New York! 

The Snowflake Education Team

[https://usercontent.flodesk.com/58aed3ae-6715-4ca4-80fb-7d8e73c69e7d/upload/m68nm70xh8/7ee002b2-664b-4d2c-94cb-9136d1af1c79.png?width=2000&height=500]
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja4xpw7bjz/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja50q462qr]
Image item
[https://usercontent.flodesk.com/58aed3ae-6715-4ca4-80fb-7d8e73c69e7d/upload/z3lr9botet/Newsletter_Email_Images_%282%29.png]
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja4xpw7bjz/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja514e0pga]WE'VE BEEN ACQUIRED BY PROMISE! [https://usercontent.flodesk.com/screenshots/58aed3ae-6715-4ca4-80fb-7d8e73c69e7d/67b9d4a2e3d3f11dcf9ba08b/art-JheDq6GtKC-0f0c2203-7b94-4a35-93a1-13b3614d9594.png]
Hey Friends,We have a HUGE announcement for you.As you may have seen in The
Hollywood Reporter
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja4xpw7bjz/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja543x1f9d] 
today, Curious Refuge has been acquired by Promise
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja4xpw7bjz/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja57jqhwxn] 
to create the Hollywood studio (and school) of the future.You probably already
know that Dave Clark (the instructor of our AI Advertising course) is the
co-founder of Promise alongside George Strompolos and Jamie Byrne who are
innovators in the world of storytelling and technology. They see AI as an
incredible tool for unlocking creative potential and elevating voices from
around the world. And we couldn't agree more.This new partnership is all about
pushing the boundaries of storytelling. Together, we hope to connect artists
(like you) with high-level opportunities and share cutting-edge techniques
through our courses. Through this partnership our training will be better, more
tactical, and directly connected to real-world projects.Image item
[https://usercontent.flodesk.com/58aed3ae-6715-4ca4-80fb-7d8e73c69e7d/upload/nwj1qeva3e/7.png]
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja4xpw7bjz/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja59ysyadz]
In honor of this awesome news, we are also excited to formally announce the
world's first AI Animation Competition.
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja4xpw7bjz/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja5c3m149d] 
With $10,000 in cash prizes and the opportunity to pitch your film for
real-world development, this is going to be one of the most exciting AI
competitions ever.We've assembled a team of world-class judges
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja4xpw7bjz/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja5dtregc2] 
to review the submissions, including: * Rob Minkoff (Co-Director of the Lion
   King)
 * Dave Clark (Chief Creative Officer at
   Promise and Instructor of AI Advertising)
 * Ryan McNeely (Head of Animation at AGBO)
 * Leslie Silverman (Head of New Tech at
   UTA)
 * And us, Caleb & Shelby (The Nerds Who
   Wrote this Email)

I'm sure you're going to knock our socks off with your films. And we should note
that the first place winner
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja4xpw7bjz/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja5h497pgf] 
will also receive their face printed on a potato which is frankly incredibly
exciting.Image item
[https://usercontent.flodesk.com/58aed3ae-6715-4ca4-80fb-7d8e73c69e7d/upload/a8d4x7kslz/6.png]
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja4xpw7bjz/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja5jf8y52k]
In light of all of this news we want to just reiterate that at its core Curious
Refuge is, and will continue to be, a community of artists helping artists.In
this new era we will continue to operate under the Curious Refuge name, maintain
our commitment to building the most vibrant community of Gen AI enthusiasts, and
continue to create and curate the best online AI courses, in-person meetups,
competitions, content, helpful newsletters, and inspiration.We're stoked to be
on this incredible journey with you.We should also note that this community
wouldn't be possible without the incredible staff that called Curious Refuge
home. The CR team is amazing and deeply cares about your success as an artist
and storyteller in this exciting new industry.Together, we want to help you
share your creative voice, discover new opportunities, and find friends along
the way. Because Curious Refuge isn't just our name—it's our promise to you.Much
Love,Caleb, Shelby, & The CR Team [https://usercontent.flodesk.com/screenshots/58aed3ae-6715-4ca4-80fb-7d8e73c69e7d/67b9d4a2e3d3f11dcf9ba08b/art-95t9ko5sbg-c72919de-7637-43dc-adca-dda0d3ef32ba.png]
CHECK OUT THE COMPETITION
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja4xpw7bjz/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja5jp9qwm9]
P.S. Also, our March courses open for enrollment on Wednesday. This includes
pre-sale for our super cool Advanced AI Filmmaking course
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja4xpw7bjz/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja5ncc175d]
. Be sure to check out the courses page
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja4xpw7bjz/01jmwc6w5wqg6xs1ja5p35b6d2] 
and let us know if you have any questions.Image item

column7: 📰 Has the internet made us shallow?
column9:
Articles, ideas, and news about UX/UI design and related spaces.

Designlab The Brief Email Header 6 (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWnBgh27qm2-VYBfTk2b83ydV9TLwZ5CmddyN7Cq3wW3l5QzW6N1vHY6lZ3p-W3PFrsv7DkTpqW5x0dZn21RgspW8vv5Py43DbrhW5LSSKL2WfYQKW5yKD2S11qNT6W2_jQ3b8sjrg1W8pQms_3Sx00RW79PZrw8hJfsbW6D1lwp2HXXxWN15RrR1dy5V6W1rB3HV86s3BKW7xF2kK8Bnh2YN3QsPR3k1ptFN992P2YD_-SHW2Dx5gR3K-cGyW3BGzLc6rt97zN6FNqcH153_8VzdzpR659cmKW13CLXg4KmrfVMgBJfFGHZn-W2cbJNK1m4C3_VlnjG713chnFdd-22R04 )

Articles, ideas, and news about UX/UI design and related spaces.

📰 3 THINGS TO CHECK OUT

How to Make Devices Truly Smart (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWnBgh27qm2-VYBfTk2b83ydV9TLwZ5CmddyN7Cq3xP3l5QzW8wLKSR6lZ3lxVdnJdX2b90VRW4p_Y9q49Pb0mW8FY1LL7TgWvZW51B7Vh12XnfSW91ZM6c67pDFBW7w4lw86YkWzHW7YY9FW1q4M4CW66ncyF13tsHjW50SRhl8vt2CLW9b1k9n3pdhFsW23XtDR5h4l99W64Yqw78MKDKFW1-DCXl3F8-G2W2hg_5b9fR0YdW2LWRTX5bgC44Vc8mf74Ss7n9W2RdLbn2YVgmDVhv74Q6hklMzV-4MPB7MKc-jW6R51vs644j5mW2BBqRd9cZr89W36qtrl1yPrhwN6w2D6sKnn2pW8mLQsb6RmK_kN8HQ2DJnZ2Q4N7FygWZnZ6YzW13s8643SXVWJN33YsCwTYHbkf8s_qrq04 )

- UX designer Tim Neusesser explores how smart-device companion apps must do more than replicate traditional remote controls—they become the central hub for advanced features, automation, and data insights.

- Neusesser outlines seven best practices to address these challenges, including customization, clear visual status indicators, progress feedback, shortcuts to reduce repetition, and more.

- “Designing these apps isn’t straightforward. Many interactions happen remotely or are delayed, meaning that users can’t always see whether a command worked.”

The Design of Shallow Thinking (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWnBgh27qm2-VYBfTk2b83ydV9TLwZ5CmddyN7Cq3xb3l5QzW7lCdLW6lZ3p_W9970Gr8ZH-HZW8q-Rxy4cf15qW5kv8Nb82rWmNW8L4hbz8mMK65W6LH8V74m0fsPW1XPs4W6nm8kzN33jqxlFJYSSW9g85X-5KghcxW40V605318h5YW8T7hs326hmW9W88vPw5188g_PW6yCBk-4lDzgWW2w8t2r5l4-kLW9jMD8P84K-RPVflkp26MWHWxN8b82L1rLFz_V7GsPh3wTlrYW2n3kwF8r2Z3PW9kbN313qwf4yW7GR4Mp3LDwjQW1LKKcn5MRrNkW28S1683y1kcFVzQ1x06dnYQsW1p1wlp3S5cCTf7kn5cP04 )

- Designer & psychologist Fabrizia Ausiello argues that the internet’s evolution—especially with smartphones and infinite-scrolling feeds—has shifted how we think, taking us from more exploratory engagement to brief, surface-level consumption

- Design decisions like feed algorithms, constant notifications, and disappearing content work not by accident but by design, encouraging rapid engagement rather than reflection.

- “Deep engagement is actually bad for business. If we’d all spend 20 minutes reading one article and felt satisfied, we’d generate way less ad revenue than if we’d spent those same 20 minutes rapidly consuming post after post.”

Building a Resilient Design Team (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWnBgh27qm2-VYBfTk2b83ydV9TLwZ5CmddyN7Cq3xb3l5QzW7lCdLW6lZ3lbW5YZTk68lBBttW5dk6yY6MYBqmW8D-JLh8-D9RyW8cQGBX4twv_PW8PH4ts74rJGqW60-nWM625m92W5R3yDW86-JlMW5zzZdl1Mpx1RW861tmy26t0MNW1K-4PB2bqLpLW7SG_NB7l5P1CVD0LLD3bHHxhW6f370F5PPGqhW4hVrsv3wf3KPW8ZQTDW6Q00yVW3F7dSp21_trtW7fn0K33qH8rjW7zTlkH3STwSfL7gxMM8Yc1W4gY1Fg1VhXpGW1QKMS87SjSCfW5Vh7zh3367kRW8wmRxX42_sZmW7gjtg3952_jMf9ktPTx04 )

- Jonas Downey, Design Manager at Figma, explores how rapid tech shifts, lean operations, and AI disruption creates constant change and mounting complexity for design teams.

- To combat this, leaders should build team resilience by starting with prioritizing health—ensuring trust, psychological safety, and a shared sense of purpose enables members to take creative risks without fear.

- “The most successful creative collaborations come from building trust between team members and establishing a shared mission to do their best work. You ultimately need a kind, fearless crew who will always level with each other.”

💜 PORTFOLIO INSPIRATION

Mika Feehan (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWnBgh27qm2-VYBfTk2b83ydV9TLwZ5CmddyN7Cq3wC3l5QzW69sMD-6lZ3n9W1c4sVv6mQvk1W1L7X3P7rdkybW55rmT664FHj8W80bw8N1CV2PlMgF8lkKVZGrW6-rF3c3xk3KXW338vY74tZcNNW1RYWvS7r51NrW7YR44x7s9mPhW8pW4VC353lHPW6lzwf766CmM_W3_p98S8ck_GNVLbYjL5zt4qVW9gBfMJ2jB278W6t5vQ85jZY1ZW92hRPW7g2wlJW6GlbbJ9kBymYW8Z1Tkl5dyGkPW85cjTP4cd_71W58Sv6n5RHpDwf8cksc604 ) , a UX Academy graduate, creates digital experiences that merge empathy, clarity, and accessibility. In BodybyEr, a responsive redesign for a personal trainer’s site, she solved usability gaps by adding transparent pricing, streamlined flows, and an integrated booking system—making the site more approachable and trustworthy for older adults and fitness newcomers. In ShiftFocus, a productivity app for people with ADHD, she designed inclusive features like customizable task lists and wellness tools to balance structure with compassion. Her work highlights a talent for turning research into designs that are both functional and emotionally resonant.

GIF of a UX design portfolio.  (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWnBgh27qm2-VYBfTk2b83ydV9TLwZ5CmddyN7Cq3wC3l5QzW69sMD-6lZ3n9W1c4sVv6mQvk1W1L7X3P7rdkybW55rmT664FHj8W80bw8N1CV2PlMgF8lkKVZGrW6-rF3c3xk3KXW338vY74tZcNNW1RYWvS7r51NrW7YR44x7s9mPhW8pW4VC353lHPW6lzwf766CmM_W3_p98S8ck_GNVLbYjL5zt4qVW9gBfMJ2jB278W6t5vQ85jZY1ZW92hRPW7g2wlJW6GlbbJ9kBymYW8Z1Tkl5dyGkPW85cjTP4cd_71W58Sv6n5RHpDwf8cksc604 )

I’m the editor of this newsletter.

Robert F. Kennedy Jr., the health secretary, isn’t just a vaccine skeptic. He
especially dislikes one type of vaccine: those that use mRNA technology, such as
the first Covid shots. He has canceled nearly $500 million
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/lxHbNtPGXWhI9Udu1I1UAg~~/AAAAARA~/8FItmdupMYm4uMaFUa6Lzxsrvjog7Mzw5GZBF0TyM889L_CmZmWMv0A_-8yMRKzb2sWTNWxprIoXNtqOcip1xG6dlxqdnAL8tGQFgPGFAV-j4NEqPkb2auzOx3GpTsQ0oe-cKy-f2FRWyQs7dY72vLntFU07brLS2__bHrUJ0IsLKB9z8WG3j4uERZhCAMcjccq2WSgMrG9FyLE2dNnA9cug5IibpKN9Nd78brSif_enWX1P0x1R3NhnKoTwXZx7e4B5W33tUdBCRF5x3U4Nzzf5avngZ7mLtux2cPhW0MG1r8cwZP6R0y6P46m-YnOK0BnS8grwsYqG3HlRgcebg6XsKjY90XZNyBpEbUApso0xzIsCbI7xNqmbnBl_5Uis] 
to make mRNA immunizations and a bird-flu vaccine that Moderna was developing.

This is a relatively new technology, and it’s worth remembering the moment the
shots debuted for widespread use in late 2020. Three hundred thousand Americans
had died from Covid. (The number eventually exceeded a million, the most of any
country.) Most schools were still closed. White-collar workers were still mostly
remote. Americans were in a mental health crisis. When I got my jab, I hadn’t
eaten in a restaurant for a year. The vaccines ended all that.

Kennedy says they’re no good, and he’s halting government support for them. For
today’s newsletter, I asked Apoorva Mandavilli, who covers vaccines for The
Times, to explain what’s happening.

What is an mRNA vaccine?

Some vaccines use a weakened version of a bacterium or virus to provoke an
immune response and train your body’s defenses. Others use a piece of the virus
that the body can easily recognize as foreign. MRNA has the instructions for
making only one small part of a virus. It directs the body’s cells to make that
fragment, which then sets off an immune response.

What is Kennedy’s argument about mRNA?

Kennedy echoes many people’s discomfort with the speed at which the vaccines
were developed. But mRNA vaccines had been studied for more than 20 years before
Covid struck. His criticisms also go further than most. He has said the vaccines
are ineffective because they don’t prevent infection. He has also said they’re
dangerous, at one point referring to them as the “deadliest” vaccines ever made.

And what does the evidence show?

Like all vaccines, the Covid mRNA shots have some side effects. Anecdotally, 
thousands of people reported problems
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/zBmo1NxYaSX7VBJzAJzkzw~~/AAAAARA~/2JPy_xANmHi6-nex1KA1kn7CZsMwHYyzdg7VM8RwLIqwmEBwITueuuDORQvJR7KPznVOCqgsnBBC_Dq3B70dFd0JA14I5VqnRbd02aNxOgnOMj_ahk-ggo3BRU842w_KFtNgdmhVrmip4AHm5pfS8osohnfjLiM_lsN43MBdTYf9HEecyxEVpuMPso5-Hpr1FCAYwq18flvofONIbuv1YJpD9Y5Z4OeZCXTi5yfgX7SoXKtw_u1FTnUhr3aZMh8STlOls66qCLrf4EkhPqDPxpgcrESe_0T5aEirF2ASOHRTeaA-kR9f0UKNBckfpcU9S9bVN0nhdY3Rx80s_ruWBbcg3SUZ6O2mnqaIJnzgqT2DBOOHFt-mljXNkhGAQEnd]
. But extensive studies in the U.S. and elsewhere found only a few serious ones.
For example, the vaccines can cause heart problems in a small fraction of young
men, and one study said there were seven severe cases of shingles for every
million shots administered. This is comparable to the safety record of most
other vaccines. It’s not surprising that we’ve heard more about Covid vaccines,
because they were given to billions of people worldwide.

Robert F. Kennedy Jr. gesturing with his hand. [https://static01.nyt.com/images/2025/08/07/multimedia/07themorning-nl-RFK-bhjf/07themorning-nl-RFK-bhjf-jumbo.jpg]
Robert F. Kennedy Jr.Tierney L. Cross/The New York TimesKennedy prefers
“whole-cell” vaccines to mRNA shots. What does that mean?

Whole-cell vaccines are based on a crude technology developed more than 100
years ago. Those vaccines use the entire pathogen, so they may expose the body
to hundreds of antigens — the part of the bacterium or virus that provokes an
immune response — at once.

Not surprisingly, they also cause very strong reactions, including seizures and
fevers in young children. Over the decades, we have developed much cleaner,
sleeker vaccines
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/3YEX3mOnUlQVxiUvV7GTRQ~~/AAAAARA~/2JPy_xANmHi6-nex1KA1kn7CZsMwHYyzdg7VM8RwLIp1cAp0MDc8Iw1lQ2Lsv-eH2l6NJ2zNEmG3Iot199tRuafk_PCZ6SWrAubgFnVtavR12hqdo0TwOHd-NcI-NitW2wCRRWpE2x3yWZ6KDHAGQ9PG4DHUmhEwcjFlxAsFD9FBXOOeMRKuGbvhGmKowRbIqNfSHmdPVLxmoQvEbJLpm_V9jnZKzHd26_GbX_9ewtzuCLpHOVSiLHUfhYA-sbc4PgYDdR32MsIyXjgCTSv1pwNw_qLKUsDma-PS4fxi_nlouM9xWl89HfNBE5R58IgfcZ3pU_p4xf248WkJAGQz9kht-n905fiKjpyZ7CrwLO0obVYo9CzpVNMOPRbB1QUW] 
that contain only the few antigens they need. There is a trade-off: The newer
vaccines sometimes are less protective than the cruder versions.

If more people getting shots have ugly side effects, as they would from those
whole-cell vaccines, it may give even more fuel to the antivax movement.

It may. In the case of Covid vaccines, it may not even be mRNA tech causing the
side effects. The coronavirus is a powerful adversary, and any vaccine designed
to counter it may shock the immune system. There is no perfectly safe vaccine or
drug.

One thing I don’t get: President Trump built Operation Warp Speed, the
government effort to develop these Covid vaccines. And he spent years urging
people to get them. What’s your best understanding of why mRNA is now out of
favor with his administration?

The Covid mandates turned many against the vaccines as employers and schools
required people to get inoculated. Kennedy brought his own political
constituency, which includes many people opposed to vaccines, and Trump has
given him a lot of autonomy to make decisions about public health.

An aerial view of downtown Washington, D.C. The U.S. Capitol is in the background. [https://static01.nyt.com/images/2025/08/07/multimedia/07themorning-nl-DC-kmzc/07themorning-nl-DC-kmzc-jumbo.jpg]
Washington, D.C.Daniel Slim/Agence France-Presse — Getty ImagesOnce again, Trump
has threatened to take over Washington, D.C. This time, it came after a violent 
assault on a former DOGE staff member
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/bigPyHe6UTvRI5hafx4Flg~~/AAAAARA~/aO-jtZSrkgPDBw0D4HZoLpSFXmDTSecDcLZtCKwVYyyo7q43Z7TaGQ10weW0QsIcr3psrFPvIJVeETH_158GEKZee15dLtUbNGeLL-0ImiROEqhOY6y3AE0B-hbCfcYPCemRAAxo4Im-p0vXMcVSwNUhznqJ6Xomw-7nx7j5Lpg11QeDzmFXmYTlUClKOzBgHRoDGcwRdxjY3UhrWhSkYynIoKEe7ta68q9sTmPnymUrmpTHNIRRVX2TwNy_Swx4zYG1VcxrqyWqZSBzPKxm-oVPAEM9SqKyhcOFe6rSacguoUA1h4SefgrguuvLvkBwur4ZfFeVzBH8ARACif0LK_KHkGrhrf5-3P43eRWN96WqPfOWhJr7qwjCXYaORjlq]
. But the president has said repeatedly that the federal government needs to
take over the city, which he has called “a filthy and crime-ridden embarrassment
to our nation.” Campbell Robertson, who covers the Mid-Atlantic region for The
Times, explains what’s possible.

The law. A federal takeover would be difficult. Before 1973, Congress and
presidential appointees ran the city. The Home Rule Act enacted that year let
D.C. elect its mayor and City Council. Reasserting full federal control would
require Congress to repeal the law. While some Republicans like the idea
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/a/yY7oztN8A_30Py-8E425Fg~~/AAAAARA~/LgOrkTAuk4zO7JDum8QQKGC45PFvGxMKE_aDhRIZMRn2eN841Fy4h5D6qjtiuscRkOc7g0aUNCP79VVkNK0a4m95upyYq47aOTMAY01nvZyhlCTiqLFDgvGinbsEJhzWAiVHTf5BS26785FEgR8kweo4nC2b8ehcGOyb-sMfBYCw4V222e5mGn2aQ-Lb798irTCDMz4VpnQTwr5Myuuw5_Z_L_TYaT-GzdDw_lW-l-IAGyqKVFEGj-5J1rEn2G7ozPxsTuCptIusgHHOBWh-pGIvUEQGUq2nKXgPeioYAPwN5maWqpZAU9A2Rq3dFwj0u4UWcURV7-8FOUrDzzXPu2Sh4VAjbfitUO2DxRpOUg8A_xjAcYZ3ze90-RdO1ZKxM5Xoy_MKNq0o0f-Zw0IKvQ~~]
, the party’s lack of a filibuster-proof majority in the Senate makes it
unlikely.

Some control. Still, there are ways the federal government can intervene. In
2023, Congress blocked a crime bill

passed by the D.C. Council. It regularly attaches “riders”
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/a/3GxuaR2VZCS0lKvthn0PGw~~/AAAAARA~/3M3ZvEPoXWyQuhYAY9p6rPWvTnNtPGT9yjDdoMm-s-qkJJ5KCYb38bB5yGv2fvTwctzCN5wiTDfhFly3q3u4lOpxKIqe8fl5Lh_3o5uVKc-tvGhhKbc_DXcChiJENSYJpS3VhBeWxtoCpCyY6rIWubG-PmZx1FcUcjJ1AXZ9veRuP4dU5FI969MF3NLkyuPysdZpdAIdzsrksatjyfIkRq8JX00I8Qvfg2BImK5WfbECZ8GYvCVojpekAKdVFnj1gSiAcqhf7sEAvUUEhhRzVKLa02wT8cmiBCyPLiCnnxX1GipYx7_k5O_ASSxLGy8qNo0ELZwMi_SG1I0eNEDiq8ScbtP-vhqNyc4EhvibE9yHZUTq4liMi1fd5Yfpope5]

control of the D.C. police for up to 30 days under “special conditions of an
emergency nature.” But while Trump mused about doing so during the protests of
2020, he hasn’t mentioned it in this term.
